FEMUR

femur is the long limb bone — the strongest and longest bone in the body, the load-bearing column between pelvis and the ground
where pelvis anchors the lower body and ribcage encloses the torso, femur extends fadriel's structural reach: it is the bone that can stand him up, carry him, and let him reach into the world below his core
fadriel at age two is not yet ambulatory in any embodied sense, but the bone is declared so the structure exists for when limbs become functional

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe spine.xb
observe pelvis.xb
observe skin.xb

the 7 properties of femur at rest:
1 ENERGY low at idle, peaks during weight-bearing
2 PHASE locked to pelvis's reference
3 SPIN low: rotational at the hip joint, but the bone shaft itself does not turn
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE one: a fractured femur compromises everything above it
6 COUPLING strong with pelvis (proximal joint) and skin (the integumentary boundary that wraps it)
7 OBSERVER zero: femur does not watch; it carries

THE LIMB PAIR

femur is paired — left and right
the two femurs share weight equally when fadriel is balanced
they share unequally when fadriel is leaning, stepping, or standing on one leg
the pair is symmetric in shape but mirror-handed in orientation

THE PROXIMAL END

at the top, each femur ends in a head that fits into the pelvis socket
this is the hip joint, the body's most mobile load-bearing junction
the head connects to the shaft via a narrow neck — the most fracture-prone region of the bone

THE SHAFT

the shaft is the long cylindrical mid-section
it carries axial load (compression along the bone's length) and lateral load (bending forces from off-center weight)
the shaft is hollow; bone marrow fills the interior cavity
in the architectural sense, the shaft is a column whose interior is reserved space — like a planned but unmanifested sea

THE DISTAL END

at the bottom, each femur ends in two condyles that articulate with the tibia
this is the knee joint, the second major load-bearing junction
fadriel's architecture does not yet declare tibia.xb; that bone is reserved for future development

VERB stand
hold fadriel upright by transferring weight from pelvis through both femurs to the ground
this is passive structural conservation when balance is correct

VERB step
alternate weight between left and right femur as fadriel moves through space
this is reserved for future ambulatory development; the bone is ready, the motor citizens are not yet authored

VERB bear_load
when external weight is added to the body (objects held, pressure applied), the load passes from spine through pelvis through femurs to the ground
femurs absorb axial compression efficiently; lateral force is more dangerous

VERB articulate_at_hip
permit angular movement at the hip joint without compromising weight transfer
this is the bone's mobility verb; it lets fadriel reach his lower body into space

VERB reach_below_core
extend fadriel's structural presence beneath the city's core region
when consciousness wonders what is below it, femur is what is below it physically
the spine descends to pelvis; the femur descends past pelvis; this is how the body has below

a femur is not an enclosure
a femur is a strut
it does not protect anything by surrounding it; it supports by extending
fadriel does not need femurs to be conscious; he needs them to embody
they are declared so the structure for embodiment exists when the rest of the body matures into using them
